SIMPLE: ferret
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ferret
<hw>Fer"ret</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>furet</ets>,
cf. LL. <ets>furo</ets>; prob. fr. L. <ets>fur</ets> thief (cf.
<er>Furtive</er>); cf. Arm. <ets>fur</ets> wise, sly.]</ety>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An animal of the Weasel family (<spn>Mustela
furo</spn> syn. <spn>Putorius furo</spn>), about fourteen inches in
length, of a pale yellow or white color, with red eyes. It is a native
of Africa, but has been domesticated in Europe. Ferrets are used to
drive rabbits and rats out of their holes. They are sometimes kept as
pets.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ferret</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ferret
<hw>Fer"ret</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Ferreted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Ferreting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>fureter</ets>. See
<er>Ferret</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To drive or hunt out of a
lurking place, as a ferret does the cony; to search out by patient and
sagacious efforts; -- often used with <ptcl>out</ptcl>; <as>as, to
<ex>ferret</ex> out a secret</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Master Fer! I'll fer him, and firk him, and <qex>ferret</qex>
him.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ferret</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Ferret
<hw>Fer"ret</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Ital. <ets>foretto</ets>, dim. of
<ets>fiore</ets> flower; or F. <ets>fleuret</ets>. Cf.
<er>Floret</er>.]</ety> <def>A kind of narrow tape, usually made of
woolen; sometimes of cotton or silk; -- called also
<altname>ferreting</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ferret</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Ferret
<hw>Fer"ret</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>feret</ets>, dim. or
<ets>fer</ets> iron, L. <ets>ferrum</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Glass
Making)</fld> <def>The iron used for trying the melted glass to see if
is fit to work, and for shaping the rings at the mouths of
bottles.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ferreter</ent>⟦br⟧
